eals the tactics by which young activists deployed their age, class, and gender to craft a heroic identity that justified their political participation and to help build cross-class movements that eventually paralyzed the country. Despite living under a dictatorship that sharply curtailed expression, these students gained status as future national leaders, helping to sanctify their right to protest and generating widespread outrage while they endured the regime’s repression. Students of Revolution thus highlights the aggressive young dissenters who became the vanguard of the opposition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aStudent movementszNicaraguaxHistoryy20th century. 0aStudentsxPolitical activityzNicaraguay20th century. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzNicaraguay20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31930740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477319314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477319314/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK